@realDonaldTrump Jul 28, 2020 | 01:30 PM EDT DOUG KASS How to Succeed on Fin TV and in the Financial Media * Give them that old razzle dazzle, razzle dazzle 'em Give 'em the old razzle dazzle Razzle Dazzle 'em Give 'em an act with lots of flash in it And the reaction will be

passionate Give 'em the old hocus pocus Bead and feather 'em How can they see with sequins in their eyes? - Chicago, Razzle Dazzle It is time to vent, again. As a "talking head" who has spent a lot of time on FIN TV over the last two decades, I feel I am in a position to

evaluate the financial media platform better than most - as I have witnessed it first hand. To begin with it is important not to generalize about "talking heads" - as there are numerous example of rigorous practitioners. Example of some thoughtful ones are RMP's

Jim "El Capitan" Cramer, Carl Quintanilla, David Faber,, Scott Wapner, Tom Keene, Jon Ferro, Lisa Abramowicz and, frankly, with few exceptions, most of the other moderators on CNBC and Bloomberg. However, the "talking heads" that parade in the financial media and some full time

panelists suffer from recurring characteristics. Here is what I view as the Top 10 ways which provide a recipe for "success" on FIN TV and in the financial media: Memorize sound bytes - regardless of the question, use those sound bytes in your answers. Deliver those sound

bytes confidently. Don't let others talk over you, don't let anyone question your observations and conclusions and dismiss the "contrary" (or what is not "working" now). Answer any question with authority (regardless of your body of knowledge or areas of expertise). Mention as

many "buzz words" as possible - whether or not it pertains to the question you are asked. Smirk a lot and talk as fast as possible and don't stray much from consensus. Only mention your winners (sweep your losers under the carpet) and claim whatever the market is doing on the

day of your appearance that it was obvious to you and should be obvious to others. Advertise your service (market letter, asset management, etc.) liberally on the network your appear on (in order to guarantee future bookings). Sell a subscription, tickets to a speech/show or
gather assets from retail investors who take what they see and hear on FIN TV and the financial media as gospel. Wash, rinse and repeat. @threadreaderapp unroll

@realmoney Jul 28, 2020 | 09:35 AM EDT DOUG KASS Two Trades of the Week - Shorting AAPL and MSFT I plan to step up my Apple (AAPL) and Microsoft (MSFT) short positions today and/or over the next few days. My rationale is that multiple revaluations higher has meaningfully moved

both stocks - a condition that often puts equities into a vulnerable and overbought position. I will have more on this theme in my opening missive tomorrow. Let's make (trading) shorts in Apple ($379.24) and Microsoft ($203.85) as my Trades of the Week - based on an

overbought and the valuation vulnerability delivered by the appreciation in P/E multiples so conspicuous in the last few months. I might even do some weekly puts, or sell some weekly calls, on top of my stock shorts in these two names. Position: Short $AAPL, $MSFT
